This article is a press briefing by Deputy National Security Advisor for International Economic Affairs Mike Froman and Special Envoy on Climate Change Todd Stern. They discuss the highlights of the declaration agreed upon by 17 leaders at the G8-plus-5-plus-1 meeting in Italy. The key points include the agreement that global and national emissions should peak as soon as possible, developed countries will undertake prompt action to produce robust reductions in their emissions, developing countries will take prompt action to reduce their emissions, and the parties will prepare long-term low-carbon growth plans. They also discuss the establishment of a global partnership to drive technology development and a financing package for climate change. The President's role in the meeting and the importance of the United States showing leadership on climate change are also mentioned. The briefing also touches on trade discussions and the future of global governance.